John Edward: The Language Skills the People of the World Need
Scotland's independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results of exams, with additional weight given by individual and joint successes in sport, art, music and other activities in the community.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools representing the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) are working to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement that school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of school selection.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to a man in a language that understands, it goes into his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it goes into his heart."
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use English alone if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of the final exams this year show that the most language reviews were made by independent school students.
A total of 68% of foreign language students received excellent grades.
The data collected at 74 SCIS schools show that 72% of students received an excellent rating in Mandarin, while 72% of students studying German, 69% of students studying French and 63% of students learning Spanish also received the highest possible rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today languages are considered as electoral subjects as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A survey conducted by the United Kingdom Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 revealed that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to lack of language skills.
So language skills are becoming more and more imperative in preparing young people for careers.
Because more and more jobs require language knowledge, these skills are key in a globalized world.
Regardless of career choices, those who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will experience the benefits of such long - term skills.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with foreigners, which gives him an advantage over competition.
According to a survey by YouGov involving more than 4,000 adults in 2013, 75 % of respondents in the United Kingdom do not know the language well enough to communicate on it, and France is the only language that speaks a two-digit percentage of respondents, 15 % more.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers different languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their program, while others will choose languages that are considered to be the most important in the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, in independent schools he will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are professional in the area.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which students can prepare and equip themselves with the skills needed for success, regardless of what the future holds.
There can be no disregard for the fact that today's global language business is very important for the future of each country so that it must also reflect on education.
Thus, knowledge of modern languages should indeed be seen as “international communication skills. ”
Independent schools will continue to offer language selection, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is director of the Council of Scottish Independent Schools
