North Korea announced that there is no "no chance" of unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korean Foreign Minister told the United Nations on Saturday that further sanctions increase mistrust in the United States and there is no way that North Korea will unilaterally disarm and give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said in the UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill last year", for example, stopped nuclear and missile tests, dismantled the nuclear testing station and decided to stop the development of nuclear technology and weapons.
"However, from the United States we have not received a satisfactory response," he added.
"If we do not have confidence in the United States, we have no faith in our national security. Under such circumstances there is no way that we will disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
Although Ri reiterated North Korea's famous complaints about Washington's "progressive" approach to denuclearisation that would gradually abolish sanctions in North Korea, his statement is significant because it has not rejected unilateral denuclearisation as it has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the current US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12th, when Kim made a promise to work on "the denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula", while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the United States conditioned that Pyongyang give up nuclear weapons before that.
Washington has also ignored calls to reduce strict international sanctions for North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on denuclearisation before that and increases the pressure with sanctions to enforce its goal, and even opposes the "declaration of the end of the war", added Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can throw us on our knees is only a delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases mistrust."
Ri didn't mention if there were any plans for the second meeting of Kim and Trump that the president of the United States was talking about at the beginning of the week in the United Nations.
But the minister noted that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae had held as many as three meetings in the last five months and added, "If denuclearisation had been sought by South Korea and not the US, denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a halt."
Regardless, the tone of Minister Rio's speech differed greatly from that of last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and said that targeting continental US missiles was inevitable after Evil President Trump called Kim a "human rocket" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea this year in the United Nations, praised Kim for his courage to disarm, but added that they still have a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in force until North Korea carries out denuclearisation.
Trump said on Wednesday that there is no time frame for denuclearisation and added: "It doesn't matter if it lasts two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia have voiced their view that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
But US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "Implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue strictly until full, final and verified denuclearisation is achieved."
The Security Council unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stop funding the nuclear and ballistic programme in Pyongyang.
He met with Rio at the UN main assembly and then said he would visit Pjongjang again next month to prepare for the second meeting.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit has not gone well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but North Korea called him after a few hours because of "gangster demands".
North Korea set up a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle the missile site and the nuclear complex that will take place if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He added that Kim had revealed to him that these "appropriate measures" related to the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and certain steps towards stabilising relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course in which they learn how to rest well
A new course at Harvard University allowed all students to get a good night's sleep in an effort to fight against an increasingly widespread culture of learning along with caffeine and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the world’s best university often have no idea of the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The idea of the course came after he gave a speech about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the class, a girl came to me and said, “Why did I find this out just now, in my senior year of college? ”
She said no one told her how important the dream is, which surprised me," The Telegraph told SETimes.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains how good sleeping habits help academic and sports success and generally improve health.
The professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the Executive Director of the Paul Barreira Health Service said the University decided to introduce a course after serious sleep deprivation was observed in students during the week.
A one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a dormitory where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to find out the effects of caffeine and light, how sleep deprivation affects success, and how important sleep routines are.
During the course, students also learn how long - term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
After that, a map of the campus with interactive icons is shown that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behaviour of students will not change immediately.
But we think they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know how cigarettes affect health," added Professor Cheisler.
A culture of pride for all-night learning before exams still exists, says the professor and adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality dream. Sleep also helps in combating obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it into a state of hunger and causes constant hunger.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old student in chemistry and biology from California, helped Professor Cheisler come up with a course after attending his first year of Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend his course to the entire campus.
As a next step, he plans to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar study before joining a competing institution.
Professor Cheisler recommends that students turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking. They must be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by display electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
