Almanah: The inventor of Geiger's counter · Global Voices
And now here's a page from our Almanac on "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and a few days ago ...the birth date of future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger in Germany.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, and from this invention later developed a device known as Geiger's counter.
Since then, Geiger’s counter has also become the main stronghold of pop culture, for example in the 1950 Bells of Colorado, where the main roles were seemingly incredible scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What on earth is this?"
Rogers: “It is Geiger’s counter, and it is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear atoms reacting to radiation in minerals."
Evans: "Look at that, you can hear it!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name still lives on.
