A study conducted by scientists at the National Foundation for Scotland (NTS) will follow ordinary and swampy dwarf bats, as well as brown long-smelling and river bats in the gardens of Inverewe in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile checks using hand detectors.
An expert analysis of the sound of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat voting and what species does.
Then a map of the habitat and report will be drawn up to create a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, an NTS conservation consultant, hopes to find out what habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to determine the benefits of working on habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have decreased significantly during the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affects shelters and habitat losses.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as well as flies and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks of pet cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to prey capture.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to find bugs and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct research, inspect shelters, and sometimes rescue.
The organization even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threeave in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bats inhabit Scotland live.
