The Commission's latest report on the conservation of fish and the plant and animal world of Florida (FWC) shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tide in parts of Tampa Bay Bay Bay Bay Bay.
According to the FWC, the conditions for heterogeneous algae blooming are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier .
The red tide stretches about 130 miles along the coast from the northern part of Pinellas County to the southern part of Lee County.
The flowering areas can be found about 10 miles from Hillsborough County, but in less places than last week.
The red tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
In the past week, there have been recorded average concentrations in the Pinellas district or in the relevant coastal area, low to high concentration in the Hillsborough district, common to high concentration in the Manatee district, common to high concentration in the Sarasota district or associated coastal area, common to medium concentration in Charlotte County, common to high concentration in the Lee district or associated coastal area and low concentration in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory system irritation has not been reported in northwest Florida during the past week.
